1) PROJECT OBJECTIVES¶

1) We will try to identify what kind of strategy followed the most successful teams :

    - High offenses
    - Tight defenses
    - Balance of two

2) We will valid this conclusion across four periods :

    - Period 1 - before 1920
    - Period 2 - 1920 to 1960
    - Period 3 - 1960 to 1990
    - Period 4 - 1990 to 2010

- Strike outs

d) Comment on the visual shape of the distribution of each variable

Is it symmetric?

Is there a single mode?

Is it narrow or wide?

Are there many outliers?

1) Games Won

We can see a wide histogram that is left - skewed with a single mode where Mean<Median<Mode. There are teams that won less games than the average and they produce the outliers show at the boxplot

2) Games Lost

We can see a wide histogram that is in appereance symmetric with a single mode . There are outliers up and down giving a wide shape to the histogram.

3) Run Scored

We can see a wide histogram that looks like left - skewed with a single mode where Mean<Median<Mode. There are teams that Run Scored less than the average and they produce the outliers show at the boxplot

4) Home Runs

We can see a wide histogram that is likely right - skewed with a single mode where Mean>Median>Mode. There are teams that made more Home runs than the average and they produce the outliers show at the boxplot

5) Strike outs

We can see a wide histogram that is a little left - skewed with a single mode where Mean<Median<Mode. There are teams that make less Strike outs than the average and they produce the outliers show at the boxplot more below to the box at the boxplot

6) Shut Outs

We can see a wide histogram that is likely right - skewed with a single mode where Mean>Median>Mode. There are teams that made more Shut Outs than the average and they produce the outliers above as show at the boxplot

7) Home Run Allowed

We can see a wide histogram that is in appereance symmetric with a single mode . There are some outliers up and down giving a wide shape to the histogram.

8) Errors

We can see a wide histogram that looks like left - skewed with a single mode where Mean<Median<Mode. There are teams that made less Errors than the average and they produce the outliers show at the above of the boxplot

We can see that there are two pair of fields where the correlation is quite strong :

- Game Won vs (Runs score minus runs against)  = 0.85 pearson (positive)
                                               = 0.87 spearman(positive) 
- Game Lost vs (Runs score minus runs against) = -0.85 pearson(negative)
                                               = -0.87 spearman(negative)

There are other two variables that have relative impact on the game to lost or win.

 - Game Won vs Runs score = 0.59 pearson (positive)
                          = 0.55 spearman(positive)
 - Game Lost vs Runs against = 0.61 pearson (positive)
                             = 0.58 spearman (positive)

We can see that these two variables ( Runs score , Runs against) could have a determinant impact on the strategy of the game. The rest of the pairs of fields has a very low correlation so , the impact on the game is very low or null.

    return y

New York Yankees is for far the most successful Team in baseball history. Through our Regression Model we can figure out what strategy the Team used to apply to be the Best of the Best.

According to our Model developed in Period four, we choose thirteen variables where the p-value is less than 0.05, the probability that this coefficients drop on zero is very low so, their contribution to the model is important. Between these variables we can recognize some of them are offensive tecniques and others are defensive tecniques.

The first conclusion we can deduce from here is that The Team (New York Yankees) use a combination of both strategies to be sucessful, High offenses and tight defenses.

We can analyze more deeply this strategy figuring out which proportion New York Yankees use these techniques.

-Home runs

-Earned runs
-Complete games

-Infield put outs

-Errors
